<HEADLINE>
<P>
CHARLES EMMET DALY; LONGTIME JUDGE AND ATTORNEY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Charles Emmet Daly, 89, former assistant attorney general of California and a 
longtime judge and attorney. 
</P>
<P>
Born in Montana, Daly obtained his law degree from Georgetown University and 
then joined the FBI when it was first organized. During World War II he was 
with Naval Intelligence and the Office of War Information and then joined 
Edmund G. (Pat) Brown's staff when Brown was district attorney in San 
Francisco. Daly moved to the future governor's staff when Brown became attorney 
general and later was appointed by the then-governor to the Municipal Court 
bench in San Francisco. Daly also had a private law practice in Los Angeles. On 
Feb. 17 in San Francisco. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Obituary 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA022790-0006 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 181842 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
February 27, 1990, Tuesday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Part A; Page 24; Column 1; Metro Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
119 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
FLOYD H. JERGESEN; SURGEON PIONEERED BONE IMPLANTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Floyd H. Jergesen, 79, an orthopedic surgeon who pioneered development of bone 
implants and methods to control bone infection. 
</P>
<P>
Since the 1950s, Jergesen's work focused on the human body's acceptance of 
metallic implants to replace or support bone. His early research in the field 
helped lay the groundwork for the field known as biomechanics. A technique for 
managing bone and soft tissue infections was dubbed the "Jergey Tube" after 
Jergesen developed the method to both drain wounds and administer antibiotics. 
After 34 years of teaching at the UC San Francisco, Jergesen retired from 
teaching in 1980, when he was appointed to the emeritus faculty. In San 
Francisco on Feb. 20 of unreported causes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
