<HEADLINE>
<P>
LIZ SMITH: ROONEY CONTROVERSY HAS CBS ON THE DEFENSIVE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Liz Smith 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CBS HAS been backing up to the hairbrush over the Andy Rooney controversy which 
came to be a much stickier nettle than anybody at that network wanted to grasp. 
It was like the "Jumping Cholla" cactus of Arizona; CBS was closer to the sting 
than they thought. This recent incident, wherein Andy insulted, first, gays and 
then, according to the gay magazine The Advocate, went on to insult blacks, had 
Rooney apologizing for the former, but denying doing the latter. CBS headman 
David Burke suspended Rooney for three months anyway. And now, feeling and 
thinking souls at CBS -- crawling under an avalanche of mail and protests that 
run 90% in Andy's favor -- want Burke to bring a quick end to it. 
</P>
<P>
HERE ARE some facts and thoughts you might have missed. At first, Burke fired 
Rooney straight out, totally. Andy was "out the door," as they say. The issue 
wasn't so much whether Rooney had made biased statements but that he had 
behaved in an insubordinate manner. Burke has had to take the heat for 
suspending Andy and not taking Rooney's word for it that he hadn't done what 
The Advocate said he did. But, in reality, Burke was in no position to state 
publicly what his action was for without more embarrassment. 
</P>
<P>
Those denizens of "60 Minutes," Don Hewitt, Mike Wallace and Ed Bradley, all 
went to bat for Andy, who they do not believe is a racist. They talked Burke 
into making the punishment something less than a firing. At first Burke changed 
it to a six-month suspension, then downgraded that to three. 
</P>
<P>
THE PUBLIC majority wants Andy back even if he made mistakes or didn't use good 
judgment or expressed himself sloppily. And some want Andy back no matter WHAT 
he said or did. You can whomp up a good and maybe even important argument these 
days about Andy Rooney and "free speech." And whether a man hired to give 
opinions on the air is allowed to have opinions. 
</P>
<P>
The interesting comment on all this is by writer Peter Davis of Newsday. He 
says that blandness flourishes on the Big Three networks and that the "dirty 
secret" of CBS is that an all-white, male-dominated hierarchy is extra 
scrupulous about not offending gays, blacks, women or other minorities. They 
don't intend to hire importantly from such groups if they can avoid it and so 
hope bending over backward takes off some of the heat. 
</P>
<P>
As Davis puts their philosophy, it is "See how fair we white males are -- we 
even kick people out who say anything about the rest of you guys." 
</P>
<P>
ANDY ROONEY has been asking, in effect, "How do we get out of this mess?" He 
takes the blame heaped on him -- and the praise -- to heart. He has been mea 
culpa-ing all over the place in private. He knows he didn't handle any of this 
well. Burke's problem, however, is not to be perceived as a weak manager, a 
wimp, an executive who doesn't mean what he says. 
</P>
<P>
It may be said there are no winners in this mess. But actually there can be. If 
gay radicals could believe more in "educating" the public in their favor rather 
than in dire punishments for all who offend them, they can see Andy back on the 
air as a chastened man who saw the light. Public consciousness HAS been raised. 
On the issue of racism, I think we should accept the word of a 40-plus veteran 
journalist that he didn't say those things. And he'll be watching his step in 
the future on this issue too. 
</P>
</TEXT>
